aa(lp25
VToday there is a raging debate
p26
aVas to how best we lift people out of poverty,
p27
aVhow best we release their energies.
p28
aVOn the one hand, we have people that say
p29
aVthe aid system is so broken we need to throw it out.
p30
aVAnd on the other we have people who say
p31
aVthe problem is that we need more aid.
p32
aVAnd what I want to talk about is something that compliments both systems.
p33
aVWe call it patient capital.
p34
aa(lp35
VThe critics point to the 500 billion dollars spent
p36
aVin Africa since 1970
p37
aVand say, and what do we have but environmental degradation
p38
aVand incredible levels of poverty, rampant corruption?
p39
aVThey use Mobutu as metaphor.
p40
aVAnd their policy prescription is to
p41
aVmake government more accountable,
p42
aVfocus on the capital markets,
p43
aVinvest, don't give anything away.
p44
aa(lp45
VOn the other side, as I said, there are those who say
p46
aVthe problem is that we need more money.
p47
aVThat when it comes to the rich, we'll bail out
p48
aVand we'll hand a lot of aid,
p49
aVbut when it comes to our poor brethren,
p50
aVwe want little to do with it.
p51
aVThey point to the successes of aid:
p52
aVthe eradication of smallpox,
p53
aVand the distribution of tens of millions
p54
aVof malaria bed nets and antiretrovirals.
p55
aVBoth sides are right.
p56
aVAnd the problem is that neither side is listening to the other.
p57
aVEven more problematic, they're not listening to
p58
aVpoor people themselves.
p59
aa(lp60
VAfter 25 years of working on issues of
p61
aVpoverty and innovation,
p62
aVit's true that there are probably no more market-oriented
p63
aVindividuals on the planet
p64
aVthan low-income people.
p65
aVThey must navigate markets daily,
p66
aVmaking micro-decisions, dozens and dozens,
p67
aVto move their way through society,
p68
aVand yet if a single catastrophic health problem
p69
aVimpacts their family,
p70
aVthey could be put back into poverty, sometimes for generations.
p71
aVAnd so we need both the market
p72
aVand we need aid.
p73
aa(lp74
VPatient capital works between,
p75
aVand tries to take the best of both.
p76
aVIt's money that's invested in entrepreneurs who know their communities
p77
aVand are building solutions
p78
aVto healthcare, water, housing, alternative energy,
p79
aVthinking of low income people not as passive recipients of charity,
p80
aVbut as individual customers, consumers, clients,
p81
aVpeople who want to make decisions in their own lives.
p82
aa(lp83
VPatient capital requires that we have
p84
aVincredible tolerance for risk,
p85
aVa long time horizon in terms of allowing those
p86
aVentrepreneurs time to experiment,
p87
aVto use the market as the best listening device that we have,
p88
aVand the expectation of below-market returns,
p89
aVbut outsized social impact.
p90
aVIt recognizes that the market has its limitation,
p91
aVand so patient capital also works
p92
aVwith smart subsidy to extend the benefits of a global economy
p93
aVto include all people.
p94
aa(lp95
VNow, entrepreneurs need patient capital
p96
aVfor three reasons.
p97
aVFirst, they tend to work in markets
p98
aVwhere people make one, two, three dollars a day
p99
aVand they are making all of their decisions within that income level.
p100
aVSecond, the geographies in which they work
p101
aVhave terrible infrastructure \u2014
p102
aVno roads to speak of, sporadic electricity
p103
aVand high levels of corruption.
p104
aVThird, they are often creating markets.
p105
aa(lp106
VEven if you're bringing clean water
p107
aVfor the first time into rural villages, it is something new.
p108
aVAnd so many low-income people
p109
aVhave seen so many failed promises broken
p110
aVand seen so many quacks and sporadic medicines offered to them
p111
aVthat building trust takes a lot of time,
p112
aVtakes a lot of patience.
p113
aVIt also requires being connected to a lot of management assistance.
p114
aVNot only to build the systems,
p115
aVthe business models that allow us
p116
aVto reach low income people in a sustainable way,
p117
aVbut to connect those business
p118
aVto other markets, to governments, to corporations \u2014
p119
aVreal partnerships if we want to get to scale.
