aa(lp121
VI want to share one story
p122
aVabout an innovation called drip irrigation.
p123
aVIn 2002 I met this incredible entrepreneur
p124
aVnamed Amitabha Sadangi from India,
p125
aVwho'd been working for 20 years with some of the poorest farmers on the planet.
p126
aVAnd he was expressing his frustration
p127
aVthat the aid market had bypassed low-income farmers altogether,
p128
aVdespite the fact that 200 million farmers
p129
aValone in India make under a dollar a day.
p130
aVThey were creating subsidies
p131
aVeither for large farms,
p132
aVor they were giving inputs to the farmers
p133
aVthat they thought they should use, rather than
p134
aVthat the farmers wanted to use.
p135
aa(lp136
VAt the same time Amitabha was
p137
aVobsessed with this drip irrigation technology
p138
aVthat had been invented in Israel.
p139
aVIt was a way of bringing small amounts of water
p140
aVdirectly to the stalk of the plant.
p141
aVAnd it could transform
p142
aVswaths of desert land into fields of emerald green.
p143
aVBut the market also had bypassed low income farmers,
p144
aVbecause these systems were both too expensive,
p145
aVand they were constructed for fields that were too large.
p146
aVThe average small village farmer
p147
aVworks on two acres or less.
p148
aa(lp149
VAnd so, Amitabha decided that he would take that innovation
p150
aVand he would redesign it from the perspective
p151
aVof the poor farmers themselves,
p152
aVbecause he spent so many years listening to what they needed
p153
aVnot what he thought that they should have.
p154
aVAnd he used three fundamental principles.
p155
aa(lp156
VThe first one was miniaturization.
p157
aVThe drip irrigation system
p158
aVhad to be small enough that a farmer only had
p159
aVto risk a quarter acre,
p160
aVeven if he had two,
p161
aVbecause it was too frightening, given all that he had at stake.
p162
aVSecond, it had to be extremely affordable.
p163
aVIn other words, that risk on the quarter acre
p164
aVneeded to be repaid in a single harvest,
p165
aVor else they wouldn't take the risk.
p166
aVAnd third, it had to be what Amitabha calls
p167
aVinfinitely expandable.
p168
aVWhat I mean is with the profits from the first quarter acre,
p169
aVthe farmers could buy a second
p170
aVand a third and a fourth.
p171
aa(lp172
VAs of today, IDE India, Amitabha's organization,
p173
aVhas sold over 300,000 farmers these systems
p174
aVand has seen their yields and incomes
p175
aVdouble or triple on average,
p176
aVbut this didn't happen overnight.
p177
aVIn fact, when you go back to the beginning,
p178
aVthere were no private investors
p179
aVwho would be willing to take a risk on building a new technology
p180
aVfor a market class that made under a dollar a day,
p181
aVthat were known to be some of the most risk-averse people on the planet
p182
aVand that were working in one of the riskiest sectors, agriculture.
p183
aa(lp184
VAnd so we needed grants. And he used significant grants
p185
aVto research, to experiment, to fail,
p186
aVto innovate and try again.
p187
aVAnd when he had a prototype
p188
aVand had a better understanding of how to market to farmers,
p189
aVthat's when patient capital could come in.
p190
aVAnd we helped him build a company, for profit,
p191
aVthat would build on IDE's knowledge,
p192
aVand start looking at sales and exports,
p193
aVand be able to tap into other kinds of capital.
p194
aa(lp195
VSecondarily, we wanted to see if we could export
p196
aVthis drip irrigation and bring it into other countries.
p197
aVAnd so we met Dr. Sono Khangharani in Pakistan.
p198
aVAnd while, again, you needed patience
p199
aVto move a technology for the poor
p200
aVin India into Pakistan,
p201
aVjust to get the permits,
p202
aVover time we were able to start a company
p203
aVwith Dr. Sono, who runs a large
p204
aVcommunity development organization in the Thar Desert,
p205
aVwhich is one of the remote and poorest areas of the country.
p206
aVAnd though that company has just started,
p207
aVour assumption is that there too
p208
aVwe'll see the impact on millions.
p209
aa(lp210
VBut drip irrigation isn't the only innovation.
p211
aVWe're starting to see these happening all around the world.
p212
aVIn Arusha, Tanzania, A to Z Textile Manufacturing
p213
aVhas worked in partnership with us,
p214
aVwith UNICEF, with the Global Fund,
p215
aVto create a factory that now employs 7,000 people, mostly women.
